newsitem.title: USA: CBOT soybeans end down on expected sales, weather.
newsitem.headline: CBOT soybeans end down on expected sales, weather.

text.p: CBOT soybean futures ended near session lows, under pressure from an anticipated jump in farmer sales and good weather in South America, traders said.
"The (South American) weather is very bearish for corn and beans," said Victor Lespinasse, vice president with Dean Witter brokerage in Chicago.
Both Argentina and Brazil continued to have warm weather with periodic rains, which should help boost the size of those country's soybean crops, traders said.
Speculators were also sellers of futures in anticipation of a wave of fresh farmer sales after the new year, traders said.
The market also fell on ideas that demand for soybean meal as hog feed would fall after the government forecast a smaller-than-expected U.S. hog herd on Friday.
Weekly USDA soybean export inspections of 25 million bushels was seen as moderately supportive to the market. Traders had been looking for exports ranging from 25 to 30 million bushels.
Soybeans ended down 3-1/4 to nine per bushel, with January down 7-1/4 at $6.94-1/4 and March down 6-1/4 at $6.90-1/2.
